# Duplicate Detective
# AI finds duplicate or near-duplicate files in a library by reading content, not just names.

[var: SITE = https://microsoft.sharepoint-df.com/teams/ZachDemos/]
[var: LIBRARY = https://microsoft.sharepoint-df.com/teams/ZachDemos/Marketing%20Assets/]

[section: setup]

Verify the "Marketing Assets" library exists with 8 files including the
intentional duplicates. This demo is read-only.

[navigate: ${LIBRARY}]

[open-chat]

[new-chat]

Confirm all 8 files are visible: Brand-Guidelines-2024.pdf, Brand Guide
Final.pdf, brand_guide_BACKUP.pdf, Sales-Deck-Q3.pptx, Q3 Sales Deck -
FINAL.pptx, Event-Banner.png, event-banner-v2.png, Case-Study-Fabrikam.docx.

[pause]

[section: demo]

[navigate: ${LIBRARY}]

Eight files in a marketing library. How many are actually unique? This happens
on every marketing team — multiple versions, backups, files with slightly
different names. Let's find out what's duplicated.

[pause]

[open-chat]

[prompt: Scan this library for duplicate or near-duplicate files. Group them together and tell me which version in each group is the most complete or most recent.]

[wait]

Copilot found three groups of duplicates. The Brand Guidelines have three
versions — it identified "Brand Guide Final" as the most complete because it
includes the January 2024 update. The sales decks are a pair, with the FINAL
version having an extra competitive positioning slide. And the event banners
are near-dupes. Point out that the Case Study is flagged as unique.

[pause]

Now let's get actionable.

[prompt: For each duplicate group, tell me which files are safe to delete.]

[wait]

It recommended keeping the most complete version in each group and flagged the
others as safe to delete. It's not just finding dupes by file name — it read
the content to figure out which version is the keeper.

[pause]

[screenshot: tools/screenshots/06-duplicate-detective-final.png]

[section: reset]

This demo is read-only. Just start a new chat.

[new-chat]
